Welcome to the speech processing world! Through this conceptual introduction, we'll see that many common speech processing tasks can basically be thought of as a series of classification tasks across time. If you have done any data annotation in Praat or ELAN, you've already done these tasks yourself: the screen recording below shows a series of annotations being placed on a Vowel tier in Praat, with each time region of interest being classified as belonging to some vowel class (heed, hair'd, etc.).

<p style="text-align:center">
    <img style="max-width:600px" src="data:image/gif;base64,">
</p>

We'll call the set of possibilities the *vocabulary*. This helps us conceptualise different speech processing tasks according to the vocabulary we're using to for classify various speech regions:

| Speech processing task       | Example vocabulary    |
|------------------------------|-----------------------|
| Voice activity detection     | Speech (S), Non-speech (N)   |
| Speaker diarisation          | SpeakerA (A), SpeakerB (B) |
| Language identification      | English (E), French (F)  |
| Automatic speech recognition (English) | a, b, c, d, ..., x, y, z |
| Automatic speech recognition (French) | a, à, â, b, ..., x, y, z |

Suppose we have a speech excerpt where there are two speakers (A, B) with speaker A asking in English (E) what the French (F) word for 'busy' is and speaker B responds that it is 'occupé'. We can see from the table below that each speech processing task (e.g. voice activity detection) essentially boils down to dividing the speech signal into small time windows (1-20) and classifying each window according to the vocabulary of the task at end (N = non-speech, S = speech).
